	<div class="explainer-card__content">
		

<p>Brown passed a triage of bills in 2014, collectively known as the <a href="https://water.ca.gov/Programs/Groundwater-Management/SGMA-Groundwater-Management">Sustainable Groundwater Management Act.&nbsp;</a></p>



<p>The law requires local agencies to begin monitoring and regulating groundwater so that withdrawals don’t exceed inflow. But this stabilization may not happen anytime soon, since the law sets a sustainability deadline of 2040.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Many farmers are uneasy because it will reduce water supply and force land out of production. Some <a href="https://www.ppic.org/blog/a-winning-approach-for-managing-groundwater-in-the-san-joaquin-valley/">experts</a> say farmers will have to fallow between 500,000 and a million acres. These changes are likely to hit hardest in the San Joaquin Valley.</p>



<p>Farmers have ideas to cope: One is to pay some not to grow anything and leave their water allocation for someone else. Another is to develop water markets to buy and sell water.&nbsp;<br></p>

	</div>

	<div class="explainer-card-footer">
		<span class="explainer-card__footer-copyright">&copy; 2020</span>
		<img class="explainer-card-footer__logo" src="https://calmatters.org/wp-content/themes/calmatters/assets/svg/calmatters-logo.svg">
	</div>
</div>



