	<div class="explainer-card__content">
		

<p>Yes. For all the high-tech ways to fortify and expand our supply, the easiest, cheapest and potentially most effective solution is to use less water to begin with.</p>



<p>The Pacific Institute, a think tank in Oakland, says that <a href="https://pacinst.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/ca-water-urban.pdf">conservation</a> could cut California’s water use half.&nbsp;</p>



<p>In fact, conservation has already helped. In Southern California, total urban demand — residences, businesses, institutions and parks — exceeded 200 gallons per person per day in the early 1990s. <a href="http://mwdh2o.com/PDF_About_Your_Water/Summary%20%E2%80%93%20Metropolitan%20Achievements%20in%20Conservation,%20Recycling%20and%20Groundwater%20Recovery.pdf">Today</a>, it&#8217;s about 130 gallons per person per day. That means a population that has grown by several million people has reduced water use by more than a third.<br></p>



